Here’s a clear breakdown of react-router-dom’s <Link> vs Next.js’s <Link> (from next/link) so you can decide which to use depending on your project.

1. Purpose & Context
react-router-dom:

External routing library for React apps.
Works in Single Page Applications (SPA) where routing is handled entirely on the client.
<Link> changes the URL without a full page reload.
Next.js (next/link):

Built-in routing for Next.js.
Supports server-side rendering (SSR), static site generation (SSG), and client-side navigation.
<Link> prefetches pages for faster navigation.
2. Basic Syntax
React Router DOM

Jsx Copy code
import { Link } from "react-router-dom";

function App() {
  return (
    <nav>
      <Link to="/about">About</Link>
    </nav>
  );
}
Uses to prop for the destination.
Works only if routes are defined in <Routes>.
Next.js

Jsx Copy code
import Link from "next/link";

export default function Home() {
  return (
    <nav>
      <Link href="/about">About</Link>
    </nav>
  );
}
Uses href prop.
Automatically prefetches in production for faster navigation.

3. Key Differences
Feature	react-router-dom <Link>	next/link
Routing Type	Client-side only	Hybrid (SSR, SSG, CSR)
Prefetching	❌ No built-in prefetch	✅ Automatic prefetch in production
File-based Routing	❌ Manual route definitions	✅ File-based routing from /pages or /app
SEO	Limited (CSR only)	Strong (SSR/SSG support)
Props	to, replace, state	href, prefetch, replace, scroll
When to Use	Pure React SPA	Next.js projects
4. When to Choose Which
If you’re in a Next.js project → Always use next/link to leverage SSR, SSG, and prefetching.
If you’re in a plain React project → Use react-router-dom for SPA routing.
Don’t mix them — react-router-dom is not needed in Next.js unless you have a very unusual use case.
✅ Recommendation:
In Next.js, stick to next/link and next/router for navigation.
In React (CRA, Vite, etc.), use react-router-dom.

